rmk: Common Snipe calling in the vicinity of a perched male Cuckoo. The Common Snipe sounds consist mainly of 'whickering' rather than drumming. Actual drumming is not that loud but occurs for around two seconds after the eighth, eleventh and twentieth seconds. The Cuckoo was calling from the same perch for around three hours. As well as its main call, it was also occasionally uttering 'choking, gurgling' notes. The latter can be heard on this clip at 0:16, 0:21, 0:25, 0:28 and, after classic calling, at 0:50, 0:53 and 0:56. I was not present to observe the scene - but it sounds as though the Cuckoo may have uttered its gurgling notes in response to the presence of the Common Snipe - because it was piqued by the proximity of the Common Snipe's overhead drumming?
